> It feels like progress is too slow, Compose Material 3 stable version has been released, and flutter Material 3 has not yet been developed

@peter100u 
To be honest, I also follow Compose, and Compose has a slow progress of Material 3, and it is quite raw, because it lags behind in time and implementation (spec mismatch) relative to Flutter and XML.  It feels like Compose's M3 will be finished when Material 4 comes out. Flutter just doesn't say as much about M3 as Compose does, I think, but it's better in line with the spec.  But what I love about Compose is the integration with Figma.  I really hope that Flutter will have this powerful tool.

What is the point of not having dedicated constructors for Elevated, Outlined and Filled cards? They are [part of M3](https://m3.material.io/components/cards/overview), and in the [m3 sample/demo](https://flutter.github.io/samples/material_3.html) they are still coded modifying the default card.

The same goes for the IconButton and other widgets... 

I am creating classes like this for each of the material 3 widgets that are not supported natively:

```
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

// https://m3.material.io/components/icon-buttons/specs#c2ca424b-2ad7-40e6-8946-47fb1918060a
class IconButtonFilledTonal extends StatelessWidget {
  IconButtonFilledTonal({Key? key, required this.onPressed, required this.icon}) : super(key: key);

  final void Function()? onPressed;
  Widget icon;

  ButtonStyle getStyle(context) {
    ColorScheme colorScheme = Theme.of(context).colorScheme;

    if (onPressed == null) {
      return IconButton.styleFrom(
        disabledForegroundColor: colorScheme.onSurface.withOpacity(0.38),
        disabledBackgroundColor: colorScheme.onSurface.withOpacity(0.12),
      );
    }

    return IconButton.styleFrom(
      foregroundColor: colorScheme.onSecondaryContainer,
      backgroundColor: colorScheme.secondaryContainer,
      hoverColor: colorScheme.onSecondaryContainer.withOpacity(0.08),
      focusColor: colorScheme.onSecondaryContainer.withOpacity(0.12),
      highlightColor: colorScheme.onSecondaryContainer.withOpacity(0.12),
    );
  }

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return IconButton(
      style: getStyle(context),
      onPressed: onPressed,
      icon: icon,
    );
  }
}

```
